# 🚀 EKS Deployment Guide — Bastion Host (Start to End)

> **Run ALL commands from inside the Bastion Host via SSH.**
> **Excludes**: Linkerd, KEDA, Resource Quotas.

---

## Phase 1: Prepare the Cluster

### 1.1 — Verify Cluster Access
```bash
aws eks update-kubeconfig --region us-west-1 --name hu-devops-lokesk26-eks
kubectl cluster-info
kubectl get nodes
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Nodes in Ready state

### 1.2 — Scale to 3 Nodes (Fix Pod Limit)
```bash
NODE_GROUP=$(aws eks list-nodegroups \
  --cluster-name hu-devops-lokesk26-eks \
  --region us-west-1 \
  --query 'nodegroups[0]' --output text)

echo "Node group: $NODE_GROUP"

aws eks update-nodegroup-config \
  --cluster-name hu-devops-lokesk26-eks \
  --nodegroup-name $NODE_GROUP \
  --scaling-config minSize=3,maxSize=5,desiredSize=3 \
  --region us-west-1

echo "⏳ Waiting for new node to join (~3 min)..."
sleep 180
kubectl get nodes
```
📸 **Screenshot**: 3 nodes Ready

---

## Phase 2: Clone CD Repository

```bash
cd ~
git clone https://github.com/Deloitte-DT-Training/HU-DevOps-Lokesk-26-CD.git cd-repo
cd cd-repo && git checkout su/cdpipeline
ls -la
```

---

## Phase 3: Create Namespaces

```bash
kubectl apply -f ~/cd-repo/namespaces/namespaces.yaml
kubectl get namespaces
```
📸 **Screenshot**: All namespaces created (frontend, backend-users, backend-products, backend-orders, database, api-gateway, monitoring, logging, argocd, sealed-secrets, security)

---

## Phase 4: Install Infrastructure Components

### 4.1 — Install Gateway API CRDs
```bash
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/gateway-api/releases/download/v1.2.1/standard-install.yaml
echo "✅ Gateway API CRDs installed"
```

### 4.2 — Install Kong Ingress Controller
> **This is the MISSING piece!** Your [gateway.yaml](file:///d:/Devops-HU/su-lokesh-cd-devops/cd/apps/api-gateway/gateway.yaml) references Kong but Kong was never installed.

```bash
helm repo add kong https://charts.konghq.com
helm repo update

helm upgrade --install kong kong/ingress \
  --namespace api-gateway \
  --set gateway.env.router_flavor=expressions \
  --set controller.ingressController.gatewayDiscovery.enabled=true \
  --wait --timeout 5m

kubectl get pods -n api-gateway
kubectl get svc -n api-gateway
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Kong pods running + LoadBalancer service with EXTERNAL-IP

### 4.3 — Wait for Kong LoadBalancer Address
```bash
echo "Waiting for Kong LoadBalancer address..."
for i in $(seq 1 20); do
  KONG_LB=$(kubectl get svc kong-gateway-proxy -n api-gateway \
    -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].hostname}' 2>/dev/null)
  if [ -n "$KONG_LB" ]; then
    echo "✅ Kong External URL: http://$KONG_LB"
    break
  fi
  sleep 10
  echo "Attempt $i/20..."
done
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Kong LoadBalancer hostname

---

### 4.4 — Install Sealed Secrets
```bash
cd ~/cd-repo/apps/sealed-secrets
helm dependency update .
helm upgrade --install sealed-secrets . \
  --namespace sealed-secrets \
  --wait --timeout 3m
kubectl get pods -n sealed-secrets
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Sealed Secrets controller running

---

### 4.5 — Install Kyverno (Policy Engine)
```bash
cd ~/cd-repo/apps/kyverno
helm dependency update .
helm upgrade --install kyverno . \
  --namespace security \
  --wait --timeout 5m
kubectl get pods -n security
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Kyverno pods running

### Verify Kyverno Policies
```bash
kubectl get clusterpolicies 2>/dev/null || echo "No policies yet (installed via Kyverno defaults)"
kubectl get policyreport -A 2>/dev/null || echo "Policy reports will appear after pod scans"
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Kyverno policy list

---

### 4.6 — Install Percona PostgreSQL Operator
```bash
cd ~/cd-repo/apps/percona-operator
helm dependency update .
helm upgrade --install percona-operator . \
  --namespace database \
  --wait --timeout 5m
kubectl get pods -n database
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Percona operator pod running

### 4.7 — Deploy PostgreSQL Cluster
```bash
kubectl apply -f ~/cd-repo/apps/postgres-cluster/postgres-cluster.yaml
echo "⏳ Waiting for PostgreSQL cluster to initialize (~3 min)..."
sleep 60
kubectl get pods -n database
kubectl get perconapgcluster -n database
```
📸 **Screenshot**: PostgreSQL pods running (instance + pgbouncer)

---

### 4.8 — Create DB Secrets
```bash
kubectl create secret generic users-db-credentials \
  --from-literal=password="securepass123" \
  --namespace backend-users --dry-run=client -o yaml | kubectl apply -f -

kubectl create secret generic products-db-credentials \
  --from-literal=password="securepass123" \
  --namespace backend-products --dry-run=client -o yaml | kubectl apply -f -

kubectl create secret generic orders-db-credentials \
  --from-literal=password="securepass123" \
  --namespace backend-orders --dry-run=client -o yaml | kubectl apply -f -

echo "✅ DB secrets created"
kubectl get secrets -n backend-users
kubectl get secrets -n backend-products
kubectl get secrets -n backend-orders
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Secrets created in all 3 namespaces

---

## Phase 5: Deploy Application Services

> Images are already in ECR from your CI pipeline!

### 5.1 — Deploy All Services
```bash
cd ~/cd-repo

helm upgrade --install frontend apps/frontend \
  --namespace frontend --wait --timeout 3m

helm upgrade --install users-service apps/users-service \
  --namespace backend-users --wait --timeout 3m

helm upgrade --install products-service apps/products-service \
  --namespace backend-products --wait --timeout 3m

helm upgrade --install orders-service apps/orders-service \
  --namespace backend-orders --wait --timeout 3m
```

### 5.2 — Verify All App Pods
```bash
echo "=== Frontend ==="
kubectl get pods -n frontend
echo "=== Users Service ==="
kubectl get pods -n backend-users
echo "=== Products Service ==="
kubectl get pods -n backend-products
echo "=== Orders Service ==="
kubectl get pods -n backend-orders
```
📸 **Screenshot**: All application pods Running

### 5.3 — Verify Services
```bash
kubectl get svc -n frontend
kubectl get svc -n backend-users
kubectl get svc -n backend-products
kubectl get svc -n backend-orders
```
📸 **Screenshot**: All ClusterIP services created

---

## Phase 6: Apply Gateway API Routes

### 6.1 — Apply Gateway + HTTPRoutes
```bash
kubectl apply -f ~/cd-repo/apps/api-gateway/gateway.yaml
```

### 6.2 — Verify Gateway Has Address
```bash
kubectl get gateway su-devops-gateway -n api-gateway
kubectl get httproute -n api-gateway
```
📸 **Screenshot**: Gateway showing "Programmed" with an address, all HTTPRoutes listed

### 6.3 — Test Routes via Kong LoadBalancer
```bash
KONG_LB=$(kubectl get svc kong-gateway-proxy -n api-gateway \
  -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].hostname}')

echo "🌐 Kong URL: http://$KONG_LB"
echo ""
echo "Testing routes..."

curl -s http://$KONG_LB/ | head -5
echo "---"
curl -s http://$KONG_LB/health
echo "---"
curl -s http://$KONG_LB/api/users
echo "---"
curl -s http://$KONG_LB/api/products
echo "---"
curl -s http://$KONG_LB/api/orders
```
📸 **Screenshot**: All API routes responding through Kong Gateway

